{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at module handoff boundaries (three source collectors -> report assembler -> summary input). A unit test of one function can miss wiring/omission bugs, but real OS/network/LLM behavior is not required: stub each source client and assert the payload sent to the summary step contains all three sections.","test_description":"Wire real report modules in-process with test doubles for metrics API, issue tracker API, deployment log reader, and summary generator sink. Execute one report run and assert the exact object/string passed into summary generation includes data from all three sources.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is resilience/orchestration across modules: source failure handling, section-level fallback, and continued report assembly. In-process stubs can reproduce the failure mode (one source raises/returns unavailable). No real network/OS dependency is required by behavior text.","test_description":"Run report pipeline in-process with one source client stubbed to fail and the other two returning valid data. Assert run completes, output report exists, failed section contains `data unavailable`, and process does not abort.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior checks summary content quality/faithfulness, which depends on model judgment in generation. Deterministic stubs can validate formatting/routing but will hide factual-drift or misrepresentation failures. Rejected Workflow because behavior describes a single summary-generation decision, not multiple model decisions in sequence.","test_description":"Execute summary generation against the real model with fixed structured inputs containing known key values and edge cases. Score outputs for factual inclusion/consistency (e.g., required-value extraction checks) over repeated runs and fail if faithfulness threshold is not met.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is end-to-end external infrastructure: real API calls/email transport/inbox delivery. Mocked transport can falsely pass while SPF/auth/routing/provider behavior fails. Rejected Agentic as minimum because assertion is inbox delivery correctness, not model-output quality; summary content can be deterministic for this test objective.","test_description":"Run the scheduled script in a production-like environment against real source endpoints (or staging equivalents) and real email delivery path to a test mailbox. Verify message is received by configured recipient, has expected subject/body structure, and includes report artifacts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure is cross-module state handoff: delivery failure -> local persistence -> next-run retry. This can be reproduced in-process by forcing sender failure and running scheduler entrypoint twice with a real local temp filesystem. Rejected System because behavior does not require validating real provider/network semantics, only correct fallback and retry state transitions.","test_description":"Use in-process pipeline with email sender test double that fails first run and succeeds second run; use real temp filesystem for fallback storage. Run scheduled job twice, assert fallback file created on first run, consumed/retried on second run, and delivery eventually succeeds without data loss.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
